Malaria Detection¶

Problem Definition¶

The context:

Malaria caused by Plasmodium falciparum is a life-threatening disease that continues to be a global concern. It is prevalent in numerous subtropical countries with limited health-monitoring systems. According to the World Health Organization, each year, hundreds of millions of individuals are affected by this disease [1]. In 2021, there were approximately 247 million reported malaria cases and an estimated 619,000 deaths. The disease is transmitted through the bites of female Anopheles mosquitoes, primarily between dusk and dawn. Global efforts are concentrated on prevention by developing vaccines and controlling mosquito populations, as well as on creating early, diverse, and reliable diagnostic tools, new treatment options, and eradication strategies.

Several methods are used for malaria detection, including rapid diagnostic tests [2], clinical diagnosis, polymerase chain reaction [3], and microscopic diagnosis. The traditional method involves trained technicians visually examining blood smears under a microscope to identify parasite-infected red blood cells. However, this process is inefficient, and the diagnostic accuracy depends on the skill of the person conducting the test. To enhance reliability and consistency, automatic image recognition systems based on machine learning have been developed to clasify malaria blood smears. Nevertheless, the practical performance has been insufficient so far [4].

References:
[1] World malaria report 2022. Available online: https://www.who.int/teams/global-malaria-programme/reports/world-malaria-report-2022 (accessed on 26 March 2023).
[2] Azikiwe, C.C.; Ifezulike, C.C.; Siminialayi, I.M.; Amazu, L.U.; Enye, J.C.; Nwakwunite, O.E. A comparative laboratory diagnosis of malaria: Microscopy versus rapid diagnostic test kits. Asian Pac. J. Trop Biomed. 2021, 2, 307310.
[3] Mirahmadi, H.; Rahmati-Balaghaleh, M.; Afzalaghaee, M.; .Zarean, M.; Shamsian, S.A.; Mehravaran, A.; Raissi, V.; Etemadi, S. Detection of malaria using blood smear by light microscopy, RDT and nested-PCR for suspected patients in south-eastern Iran. Gene Re 2021, 25, 101339.
[4] Hemachandran, K.; Alasiry, A.; Marzougui, M.; Ganie, S.M.; Pise, A.A.; Alouane, M.T.-H.; Chola, C. Performance Analysis of Deep Learning Algorithms in Diagnosis of Malaria Disease. Diagnostics 2023, 13, 534.

The objectives:

Perform an analysis of deep learning algorithms in the diagnosis of malaria from microscopic images to identify the best approach that improves reliability, accuracy and replicability of the diagnostic process.
Propose a low-cost and widely accessible integration of the selected model into a point-of-care network.

My personal objective is to use PyTorch library that I have never worked with before, with a help of tutorials [5, 6].

References:

[6] LearnPyTorch - Computer Vision. Available online: https://www.learnpytorch.io/03_pytorch_computer_vision/#03-pytorch-computer-vision (accessed on 26 March 2023 - 30 March 2023).

The key questions:

Can we use deep learning algorithms to improve the microscopic diagnostic process of malaria?

Which deep learning algorithm is most suitable for the problem?

  • Which deep learning technique best solves the problem?
  • Which classification metric is the most relevant for selecting the best deep learning model?
  • Does data augmentation improve the model's performance?

What are the low-cost and widely accessible means of implementing the selected model into the point-of-care workflow?

The problem formulation: What is it that we are trying to solve using data science?

  1. Malaria is a life-threatening disease affecting mostly subtropical nations with little health-monitoring infrastructure.
  2. Current microscopic techniques for diagnosing malaria are inefficient and highly dependent on human expertise level.
  3. Early, accurate, repricable and widely accessible diagnosis of malaria could help decrease the mortality rate of the disease.

Data Description ¶

There are a total of 24,958 train and 2,600 test images (colored) that we have taken from microscopic images. These images are of the following categories:

Parasitized: The parasitized cells contain the Plasmodium parasite which causes malaria
Uninfected: The uninfected cells are free of the Plasmodium parasites

# Loading classes and functions

# Write a custom dataset class (inherits from torch.utils.data.Dataset)
# Subclass torch.utils.data.Dataset
class ImageFolderCustom(Dataset):
    
    # Initialize with a targ_dir and transform (optional) parameter
    def __init__(self, targ_dir: str, transform=None) -> None:
        
        # Create class attributes
        # Get all image paths
        self.paths = list(pathlib.Path(targ_dir).glob("*/*.png"))
        # Setup transforms
        self.transform = transform
        # Create classes and class_to_idx attributes
        self.classes, self.class_to_idx = self.find_classes(targ_dir)
    
    # Overwrite the __len__() method (optional but recommended for subclasses of torch.utils.data.Dataset)
    def __len__(self) -> int:
        "Returns the total number of samples."
        return len(self.paths)
    
    # Overwrite the __getitem__() method (required for subclasses of torch.utils.data.Dataset)
    def __getitem__(self, index: int) -> Tuple[torch.Tensor, int]:
        "Returns one sample of data, data and label (X, y)."
        img = self.load_image(index)
        class_name  = self.paths[index].parent.name # expects path in data_folder/class_name/image.png
        class_idx = self.class_to_idx[class_name]

        # Transform if necessary
        if self.transform:
            return self.transform(img), class_idx # return data, label (X, y)
        else:
            return img, class_idx # return data, label (X, y)

    # Make function to load images
    def load_image(self, index: int) -> Image.Image:
        "Opens an image via a path and returns it."
        image_path = self.paths[index]
        return Image.open(image_path)

    # Make function to find classes in target directory
    @staticmethod
    def find_classes(directory: str) -> Tuple[List[str], Dict[str, int]]:
        "Finds the class folder names in a target directory."
        # Get the class names by scanning the target directory
        classes = sorted(entry.name for entry in os.scandir(directory) if entry.is_dir())
        
        # Raise an error if class names not found
        if not classes:
            raise FileNotFoundError(f"Couldn't find any classes in {directory}.")
            
        # Crearte a dictionary of index labels (computers prefer numerical rather than string labels)
        class_to_idx = {cls_name: i for i, cls_name in enumerate(classes)}
        return classes, class_to_idx

# Write a custom dataset class (inherits from torch.utils.data.Dataset)
# Subclass torch.utils.data.Dataset
# Converts images from RGB to HSV
class HSVImageDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, data, transform=None):
        if not isinstance(data, (Dataset, DataLoader)):
            raise TypeError("Input data should be a PyTorch Dataset or DataLoader object.")
        self.data = data
        self.transform = transform

    def __len__(self):
        "Returns the total number of samples."
        return len(self.data)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        "Returns one sample of data, data and label (X, y)."
        image, label = self.data[idx]
        hsv_image = self.convert_image_to_hsv(image)

        if self.transform:
            hsv_image = self.transform(hsv_image)

        return hsv_image, label

    @staticmethod
    def convert_image_to_hsv(image):
        "Converts images from RGB to HSV."
        if isinstance(image, torch.Tensor):
            image = image.permute(1, 2, 0).numpy()

        if isinstance(image, Image.Image):
            image = np.array(image)

        hsv_image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV)
        return hsv_image

# Write a custom dataset class (inherits from torch.utils.data.Dataset)
# Subclass torch.utils.data.Dataset
# Applies Gaussian blurring
class GaussianBlurDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, data, kernel_size, sigma, transform=None):
        if not isinstance(data, (Dataset, DataLoader)):
            raise TypeError("Input data should be a PyTorch Dataset or DataLoader object.")
        self.data = data
        self.kernel_size = kernel_size
        self.sigma = sigma
        self.transform = transform

    def __len__(self):
        "Returns the total number of samples."
        return len(self.data)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        "Returns one sample of data, data and label (X, y)."
        image, label = self.data[idx]
        blurred_image = self.apply_gaussian_blur(image)

        if self.transform:
            blurred_image = self.transform(blurred_image)

        blurred_tensor = torch.from_numpy(blurred_image).permute(2, 0, 1).float()
        return blurred_tensor, label

    def apply_gaussian_blur(self, image):
        "Applies Gaussian blurring."
        if isinstance(image, torch.Tensor):
            image = image.permute(1, 2, 0).numpy()

        if isinstance(image, Image.Image):
            image = np.array(image)

        blurred_image = cv2.GaussianBlur(image, (self.kernel_size, self.kernel_size), self.sigma)
        return blurred_image

# Utility functions

def count_labels(data_loader):
    "Counts number of labels in a data loader."
    count = 0

    for _, labels in data_loader:
        count += len(labels)

    return count

def min_max_pixel_values_single_batch(images):
    "Finds min and max pixel values for a single batch."
    min_value = torch.min(images)
    max_value = torch.max(images)
    return min_value.item(), max_value.item()

def min_max_pixel_values(loader, num_workers=512):
    "Finds min and max pixel values for a data loader."
    min_values = []
    max_values = []

    with concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=num_workers) as executor:
        futures = []
        for images, _ in loader:
            future = executor.submit(min_max_pixel_values_single_batch, images)
            futures.append(future)

        for future in concurrent.futures.as_completed(futures):
            min_value, max_value = future.result()
            min_values.append(min_value)
            max_values.append(max_value)

    return min(min_values), max(max_values)

def count_pixel_values_single_batch(images, labels):
    "Counts the number of unique pixel values for each class in a single batch."
    pixel_values = {0: [], 1: []}

    for img, label in zip(images, labels):
        img_pixels = img.view(-1).tolist()
        pixel_values[label.item()].extend(img_pixels)

    return pixel_values

def count_pixel_values_by_class(data_loader, num_workers=512):
    "Counts the number of unique pixel values for each class in a data loader."
    pixel_values = {0: [], 1: []}

    with concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=num_workers) as executor:
        futures = []
        for images, labels in data_loader:
            future = executor.submit(count_pixel_values_single_batch, images, labels)
            futures.append(future)

        for future in concurrent.futures.as_completed(futures):
            batch_pixel_values = future.result()
            for class_label in pixel_values:
                pixel_values[class_label].extend(batch_pixel_values[class_label])

    return pixel_values

def count_classes(data_loader):
    "Counts number of images foe each class in a data loader."
    class_counts = {}

    for _, labels in data_loader:
        unique_labels, counts = torch.unique(labels, return_counts=True)
        for label, count in zip(unique_labels.tolist(), counts.tolist()):
            if label not in class_counts:
                class_counts[label] = 0
            class_counts[label] += count

    return class_counts

# Visualization methods

# Take in a Dataset as well as a list of class names
def display_random_images(dataset: torch.utils.data.dataset.Dataset,
                          classes: List[str] = None,
                          n: int = 10,
                          display_shape: bool = True,
                          seed: int = None):
    "Displays randomly selected images."

    # Adjust display if n too high
    if n > 10:
        n = 10
        display_shape = False
        print(f"For display purposes, n shouldn't be larger than 10, setting to 10 and removing shape display.")
    
    # Set random seed
    if seed:
        random.seed(seed)

    # Get random sample indexes
    random_samples_idx = random.sample(range(len(dataset)), k=n)

    # Setup plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))

    # Loop through samples and display random samples 
    for i, targ_sample in enumerate(random_samples_idx):
        targ_image, targ_label = dataset[targ_sample][0], dataset[targ_sample][1]

        # Plot adjusted samples
        plt.subplot(1, n, i+1)

        if not isinstance(targ_image, Tensor):
          plt.imshow((targ_image * 255).astype(np.uint8))
        else:
          plt.imshow(targ_image.permute(1, 2, 0))
        plt.axis("off")
        if classes:
            title = f"{classes[targ_label]}"
            if display_shape:
                title = title + f"\nshape: {targ_image.shape}"
        plt.title(title)

def imshow(img, ax):
    "Plots transposed images."
    npimg = img.numpy()
    ax.imshow(np.transpose(npimg, (1, 2, 0)))

def calculate_mean_images(data_loader):
    "Calculates mean images for each class in a data loader."
    class_sums = {0: None, 1: None}
    class_counts = {0: 0, 1: 0}

    for images, labels in data_loader:
        for img, label in zip(images, labels):
            class_label = label.item()
            class_counts[class_label] += 1

            if class_sums[class_label] is None:
                class_sums[class_label] = img
            else:
                class_sums[class_label] += img

    mean_images = {label: img_sum / count for label, (img_sum, count) in enumerate(zip(class_sums.values(), class_counts.values()))}

    return mean_images

# Set the seed to a fixed value
torch.manual_seed(42)

# Paths to folders
path_to_train = '/content/drive/MyDrive/cell_images/train/'
path_to_test = '/content/drive/MyDrive/cell_images/test/'

BATCH_SIZE = 32
NUM_WORKERS = os.cpu_count()

# Write transforms for images
data_transform = transforms.Compose([
    # Resize the images to 64x64
    transforms.Resize(size=(64, 64)),
    # Turn the image into a torch.Tensor
    transforms.ToTensor() # this also converts all pixel values from 0 to 255 to be between 0.0 and 1.0 
])

# Load and transform data
train_data_custom = ImageFolderCustom(targ_dir=path_to_train, 
                                      transform=data_transform)
test_data_custom = ImageFolderCustom(targ_dir=path_to_test, 
                                     transform=data_transform)

# Train and validation split
train_ratio = 0.8
train_len = int(train_ratio * len(train_data_custom))
val_len = len(train_data_custom) - train_len
train_data_split, val_data_split = random_split(train_data_custom, [train_len, val_len])

# Create data loaders
train_dataloader_custom = DataLoader(dataset=train_data_split, # use custom created train Dataset
                                     batch_size=BATCH_SIZE, # how many samples per batch
                                     num_workers=NUM_WORKERS, # how many subprocesses to use for data loading (higher = more)
                                     shuffle=True) # shuffle the data

val_dataloader_custom = DataLoader(val_data_split, 
                                   batch_size=BATCH_SIZE, 
                                   num_workers=NUM_WORKERS,
                                   shuffle=False)

test_dataloader_custom = DataLoader(dataset=test_data_custom,
                                    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE, 
                                    num_workers=NUM_WORKERS, 
                                    shuffle=False) # don't usually need to shuffle testing data

The extracted folder has different folders for train and test data will contain the different sizes of images for parasitized and uninfected cells within the respective folder name.

The size of all images must be the same and should be converted to 4D arrays so that they can be used as an input for the convolutional neural network. Also, we need to create the labels for both types of images to be able to train and test the model.

Let's do the same for the training data first and then we will use the same code for the test data as well.

Observations and insights:

Converting RGB to HSV reveals parasites inside red blood cells as differently colored spots.

  • HSV representation is more robust to lighting variations and shadows, as the Hue component remains relatively stable under different lighting conditions. This makes it easier to identify and track objects based on their color, regardless of the illumination or shadows present in the scene.
  • Some image processing tasks, such as edge detection, noise reduction, or color-based filtering, benefit from working in the HSV color space, as it can lead to more accurate and meaningful results.
  • The HSV color space provides a better representation of how humans perceive colors, as it separates the color information (Hue) from the intensity (Value) and the saturation of the color. This can help in designing algorithms that better mimic human perception, which may improve the performance of computer vision tasks.

Think About It: Would blurring help us for this problem statement in any way? What else can we try?

Gaussian blurring could potentially help with malaria detection from microscopic images, but its effectiveness depends on the specific problem and dataset at hand. There are several ways Gaussian blurring could be beneficial, but mainly noise reduction. Microscopic images often contain noise due to the imaging process or the equipment used. Gaussian blurring can help reduce this noise, leading to cleaner images that are easier to analyze and process.

On the other hand, it's important to note that Gaussian blurring also has some drawbacks in malaria detection. Gaussian blurring can cause a loss of fine details in the image, which might be crucial for detecting subtle signs of malaria infection. Excessive blurring leads to over-smoothing of the image, making it more challenging to identify specific features related to malaria infection. Moreover, Gaussian blurring needs extensive fine-tuning to hit the precise trade-off between the advantages and disadvantages.

Apart from Gaussian blurring, there are several other preprocessing and feature extraction techniques that can be helpful in malaria detection from microscopic images. Some of these techniques are:

  • Image enhancement and segmentation
  • Data augmentation
  • Convolutional Neural Networks can be trained on the dataset to automatically learn features and perform classification tasks.
  • Pretrained deep learning models, such as ResNet or VGG, can be fine-tuned on the malaria dataset to leverage the features learned from large-scale datasets like ImageNet.
  • Combining the predictions from multiple models or techniques (ensemble methods) can improve overall performance and increase the robustness of the malaria detection system.

Building the model

In [36]:
class BaseModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(BaseModel, self).__init__()

    def forward(self, x):
        raise NotImplementedError

    def train_model(self, train_loader, val_loader, criterion, optimizer, device, num_epochs):
        "Trains the model and stores accuracies for train and validation data loaders for each epoch."
        self.to(device)
        train_accuracies = []
        val_accuracies = []

        for epoch in range(num_epochs):
            self.train()
            running_loss = 0.0

            # Train
            for i, (inputs, labels) in enumerate(train_loader):
                inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
                optimizer.zero_grad()
                outputs = self(inputs)
                loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
                loss.backward()
                optimizer.step()
                running_loss += loss.item()


            _, train_accuracy = self.evaluate_model(train_loader, device)
            _, val_accuracy = self.evaluate_model(val_loader, device)

            train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)
            val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

            print(f"Epoch [{epoch + 1}/{num_epochs}] Train Accuracy: {train_accuracy:.4f}, Val Accuracy: {val_accuracy:.4f}")

        return train_accuracies, val_accuracies

    def evaluate_model(self, test_loader, device):
        "Evaluates the model with basic performance metrics and confusion matrix."
        self.eval()
        self.to(device)
        all_labels = []
        all_predicted = []

        with torch.no_grad():
            for inputs, labels in test_loader:
                inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
                outputs = self(inputs)
                _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
                all_labels.extend(labels.cpu().numpy())
                all_predicted.extend(predicted.cpu().numpy())

        accuracy = (np.array(all_labels) == np.array(all_predicted)).mean()
        precision, recall, f1_score, _ = precision_recall_fscore_support(all_labels, all_predicted, average='weighted')
        cm = confusion_matrix(all_labels, all_predicted)

        print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
        print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
        print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
        print(f"F1 Score: {f1_score:.4f}")

        return cm, accuracy

    def plot_accuracy_curves(self, train_accuracies, val_accuracies):
        "Plots accuracy curves."
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(train_accuracies, label='Train Accuracy')
        plt.plot(val_accuracies, label='Validation Accuracy')
        plt.xlabel('Epoch')
        plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()

    def plot_confusion_matrix(self, cm, class_names):
        "Plots confusion matrices."
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=class_names, yticklabels=class_names)
        plt.xlabel("Predicted")
        plt.ylabel("True")
        plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
        plt.show()

class SimpleCNN(BaseModel):
    def __init__(self, num_classes):
        super(SimpleCNN, self).__init__()

        # First convolutional layer
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 32, kernel_size=2, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.relu1 = nn.ReLU()
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2)
        self.dropout1 = nn.Dropout(0.2)

        # Second convolutional layer
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(32, 32, kernel_size=2, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.relu2 = nn.ReLU()
        self.pool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2)
        self.dropout2 = nn.Dropout(0.2)

        # Third convolutional layer
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(32, 32, kernel_size=2, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.relu3 = nn.ReLU()
        self.pool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2)
        self.dropout3 = nn.Dropout(0.2)

        # Fully-connected layers
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(32 * 8 * 8, 512)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.4)

        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(512, num_classes)
        self.softmax = nn.Softmax(dim=1)

    def forward(self, x):
        
        x = self.dropout1(self.pool1(self.relu1(self.conv1(x))))
        x = self.dropout2(self.pool2(self.relu2(self.conv2(x))))
        x = self.dropout3(self.pool3(self.relu3(self.conv3(x))))
        
        x = x.view(x.size(0), -1) # flatten
        
        x = self.dropout(self.relu(self.fc1(x)))
        x = self.softmax(self.fc2(x))
        
        return x

# Implementing a model from reference [4] in the introduction
class ComplexCNN(BaseModel):
    def __init__(self, num_classes):
        super(ComplexCNN, self).__init__()

        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=3, out_channels=18, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=2)
        self.maxpool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout1 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)
        
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=18, out_channels=72, kernel_size=3, stride=1)
        self.maxpool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout2 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)
        
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=72, out_channels=72, kernel_size=3, stride=1)
        self.maxpool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout3 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)
        
        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=72, out_channels=72, kernel_size=3, stride=1)
        self.maxpool4 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout4 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)
        
        self.flatten = nn.Flatten()
        
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(in_features=288, out_features=72)
        self.dropout5 = nn.Dropout(p=0.5)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(in_features=72, out_features=num_classes)
    
    def forward(self, x):
        
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = nn.functional.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool1(x)
        x = self.dropout1(x)
        
        x = self.conv2(x)
        x = nn.functional.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool2(x)
        x = self.dropout2(x)
        
        x = self.conv3(x)
        x = nn.functional.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool3(x)
        x = self.dropout3(x)
        
        x = self.conv4(x)
        x = nn.functional.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool4(x)
        x = self.dropout4(x)
        
        x = self.flatten(x)
        
        x = self.fc1(x)
        x = nn.functional.relu(x)
        x = self.dropout5(x)
        x = self.fc2(x)
        x = nn.functional.softmax(x, dim=1)
        
        return x

Model 2 with Batch Normalization

In [46]:
class Complex2CNN(BaseModel):
    def __init__(self, num_classes):
        super(Complex2CNN, self).__init__()

        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=3, out_channels=18, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=2)
        self.bn1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(18)
        self.leakyrelu1 = nn.LeakyReLU(inplace=True)
        self.maxpool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout1 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)

        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=18, out_channels=72, kernel_size=3, stride=1)
        self.bn2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(72)
        self.leakyrelu2 = nn.LeakyReLU(inplace=True)
        self.maxpool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout2 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)

        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=72, out_channels=72, kernel_size=3, stride=1)
        self.bn3 = nn.BatchNorm2d(72)
        self.leakyrelu3 = nn.LeakyReLU(inplace=True)
        self.maxpool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout3 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)

        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=72, out_channels=72, kernel_size=3, stride=1)
        self.bn4 = nn.BatchNorm2d(72)
        self.leakyrelu4 = nn.LeakyReLU(inplace=True)
        self.maxpool4 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout4 = nn.Dropout2d(p=0.25)

        self.flatten = nn.Flatten()
        
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(in_features=288, out_features=72)
        self.bn5 = nn.BatchNorm1d(72)
        self.leakyrelu5 = nn.LeakyReLU(inplace=True)
        self.dropout5 = nn.Dropout(p=0.5)

        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(in_features=72, out_features=num_classes)
        self.softmax = nn.Softmax(dim=1)

    def forward(self, x):

        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.bn1(x)
        x = self.leakyrelu1(x)
        x = self.maxpool1(x)
        x = self.dropout1(x)

        x = self.conv2(x)
        x = self.bn2(x)
        x = self.leakyrelu2(x)
        x = self.maxpool2(x)
        x = self.dropout2(x)

        x = self.conv3(x)
        x = self.bn3(x)
        x = self.leakyrelu3(x)
        x = self.maxpool3(x)
        x = self.dropout3(x)

        x = self.conv4(x)
        x = self.bn4(x)
        x = self.leakyrelu4(x)
        x = self.maxpool4(x)
        x = self.dropout4(x)

        x = self.flatten(x)

        x = self.fc1(x)
        x = self.bn5(x)
        x = self.leakyrelu5(x)
        x = self.dropout5(x)

        x = self.fc2(x)
        x = self.softmax(x)

        return x

Observations and insights:

Model 0 reaches 97.62% recall, with approx. equal false positives and false negatives on the test data. Train and validation accuracy show gradual increase with a dip, most probably caused by a vanished gradient. Model 1 shows a lower recall of 94.88%, with 5x more false negatives than false positives. Train and validation accuracy show slow increase with a dip. The training is more stabilized by the model 2 architecture according to train and validation plot accuracy. The increase is steady and fluctuates without drops. The recall reaches 97.96%, with 4x more false negatives than false positives. Model 3 shows a similar recall of 97.19% but with a decreased fraction of false negatives. The course of training is a steady increase, fluctuating, without drops.

  • Model 1 addresses the key question of "Which classification metric is the most relevant for selecting the best deep learning model?".

    Recall is the ratio of true positive predictions to the sum of true positive and false negative predictions. It measures the ability of the model to identify all positive cases (i.e., malaria-infected samples). Another candidate metric is Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC-AUC) curve. This metric considers the trade-off between true positive rate (sensitivity) and false positive rate (1-specificity) for different threshold values. A higher AUC value indicates better classification performance.

    In the context of malaria diagnosis, it is crucial to minimize false negatives (i.e., malaria cases that are not identified), as this could lead to delayed treatment and potentially severe consequences. Therefore, prioritizing recall (sensitivity) might be more relevant. However, it is also important to consider the trade-off between recall and precision to avoid overdiagnosis and unnecessary treatment.

    Taken together, recall seems to be the best metric to choose since the priority is more on minimizing false negatives.

  • Model 2 addresses the key question of "Which deep learning technique best solves the problem?" with a complex multi-layered design of convolutional network suggested in reference [4] and improved with LeakyReLU to combat vanishing gradients and Batch Normalization to reduce the internal covariate shift and make training more stable and efficient.

    Internal covariate shift refers to the change in the distribution of layer inputs that happens during training as the parameters of the previous layers change. This can cause the network to converge slowly or not at all, and can also lead to the saturation of activation functions.

    Additionally, batch normalization can act as a regularizer, helping to prevent overfitting and improving the generalization performance of the model.

    Indeed, model 2 shows increased performance in comparison with the previous two.

  • Model 3 addresses the key question of "Does data augmentation improve the model's performance?" by applying TrivialDataAugment(). Research shows that random transforms generally perform better than hand-picked transforms. For trivial data augment, a number of transforms is randomly picked from a set of transforms to perform on an image and at a random magnitude between a given range (a higher magnitude means more instense).

    Data augmentation reduces the fraction of false negatives which is greatly beneficial for this task.

In [92]:
class VGG16(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes):
        super(VGG16, self).__init__()
        self.vgg16 = models.vgg16(pretrained=True)
        self.vgg16.classifier[6] = nn.Linear(4096, num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.vgg16(x)
        return x

    def train_model(self, train_loader, val_loader, criterion, optimizer, device, num_epochs):
        "Trains the model and stores accuracies for train and validation data loaders for each epoch."
        self.to(device)
        train_accuracies = []
        val_accuracies = []

        for epoch in range(num_epochs):
            self.train()
            running_loss = 0.0

            # Train
            for i, (inputs, labels) in enumerate(train_loader):
                inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
                optimizer.zero_grad()
                outputs = self(inputs)
                loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
                loss.backward()
                optimizer.step()
                running_loss += loss.item()


            _, train_accuracy = self.evaluate_model(train_loader, device)
            _, val_accuracy = self.evaluate_model(val_loader, device)

            train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)
            val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

            print(f"Epoch [{epoch + 1}/{num_epochs}] Train Accuracy: {train_accuracy:.4f}, Val Accuracy: {val_accuracy:.4f}")

        return train_accuracies, val_accuracies

    def evaluate_model(self, test_loader, device):
        "Evaluates the model with basic performance metrics and confusion matrix."
        self.eval()
        self.to(device)
        all_labels = []
        all_predicted = []

        with torch.no_grad():
            for inputs, labels in test_loader:
                inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
                outputs = self(inputs)
                _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
                all_labels.extend(labels.cpu().numpy())
                all_predicted.extend(predicted.cpu().numpy())

        accuracy = (np.array(all_labels) == np.array(all_predicted)).mean()
        precision, recall, f1_score, _ = precision_recall_fscore_support(all_labels, all_predicted, average='weighted')
        cm = confusion_matrix(all_labels, all_predicted)

        print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
        print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
        print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
        print(f"F1 Score: {f1_score:.4f}")

        return cm, accuracy

    def plot_accuracy_curves(self, train_accuracies, val_accuracies):
        "Plots accuracy curves."
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(train_accuracies, label='Train Accuracy')
        plt.plot(val_accuracies, label='Validation Accuracy')
        plt.xlabel('Epoch')
        plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()

    def plot_confusion_matrix(self, cm, class_names):
        "Plots confusion matrices."
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=class_names, yticklabels=class_names)
        plt.xlabel("Predicted")
        plt.ylabel("True")
        plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
        plt.show()

Observations and Conclusions drawn from the final model: _

Improvements that can be done:

  • Can the model performance be improved using other pre-trained models or different CNN architecture?
    • Reference [4] compares the performance of a complex CNN (here as model 1, further improved with LeakyReLU and Batch Normalization to model 2) with pre-trained networks: MobileNetV2 and ResNet50. In this paper, ResNet50 shows the best performance on the dataset. These pre-trained networks could improve the recall. These networks address the increase in training loss with increased number of convolutional layers.
  • You can try to build a model using these HSV images and compare them with your other models.
    • HSV conversion showed quite a clear shape and color definition of parasites inside red blood cells. It could help in differentiating them from cell impurities, thus improving false positivity.
  • Incorporating data augmentation.
    • Data augmentation helped reduce the fraction of false negatives. Together with HSV conversion, it could provide even better result than the best model.

Insights¶

Refined insights:¶

  • What are the most meaningful insights from the data relevant to the problem?
    • There are 24,958 train images (19,966 after splitting off the validation set of 4,992) and 2,600 test images. The data are balanced for each class for each data set. The range and distribution of pixel values do not differ significantly between classes.
    • The parasites can be of various shapes and their color can be mistaken for red blood cell impurities. The key role of color is confirmed both by mean images for each class and HSV conversion that separates parasites very well. Moreover, it's robust against changes in brightness and lighting.
    • Gaussian blurring seems to remove the sharp definition of parasites which could lead to false negatives in smaller parasite bodies.

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:¶

  • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?
    • The simple model performs relatively well. Increasing the depth of the convolutional layers leads to more instability in the training, presumably due to vanishing gradients. LeakyReLU and batch normalization improve the instability. Unfortunately, the pre-trained model VGG16 did not perform very well, underfitting severely, and would need more tuning.
    • Improvements can be introduced according to the list above.

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

  • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?
    • From the current solutions, model 2 performs the best, with 97.96% recall on test data. So far, it is the best solution due to its stability during training despite increased complexity. It has the potential to be improved by incorporating data augmentation and HSV conversion.
    • However, the potential of pre-trained models hasn't been fully explored, as suggested above.
